      "part_type": "Hadith",
      "path": "/books/al-kafi:1:2:11:6",
      "relations": null,
      "text": [
        " إِذَا سُئِلَ الرَّجُلُ مِنْكُمْ عَمَّا لَا يَعْلَمُ فَلْيَقُلْ لَا أَدْرِي وَ لَا يَقُلْ اللَّهُ أَعْلَمُ فَيُوقِعَ فِي قَلْبِ صَاحِبِهِ شَكّاً وَ إِذَا قَالَ الْمَسْئُولُ لَا أَدْرِي فَلَا يَتَّهِمُهُ السَّائِلُ ."
      ],
      "translations": {
        "en.hubeali": [
          "Ali Bin Ibrahim, from Ahmad Bin Muhammad Bin Khalid, from Hammad Bin Isa, from Hareyz Bin Abdullah, from Muhammad Bin Muslim, ",
          "(It has been narrated) from Abu Abdullah<sup>asws</sup> having said: ‘When the man from you is asked about what he does not know, so let him say, ‘I don’t know’, and he should not say, ‘Allah<sup>azwj</sup> is more Knowing’, for there would occur a doubt in the heart of his companion. And when the questioned one says, ‘I don’t know’, so the questioner cannot accuse him’."
        ],
        "en.sarwar": [
          " 6. Ali ibn Ibrahim has narrated from Ahmad ibn Muhammad ibn Khalid from Hammad ibn ‘Isa from Hariz ibn ‘Abdallah from Muhammad ibn Muslim from abu ‘Abdallah (a.s.) who has said the following. “If one of you would be asked of what he does not know he must say, ‘I have no knowledge and he must not say, “Allah knows best” because it may create doubts in the hearts of his audience. If the person questioned would say, “I do not know his audience will not accuse him of anything.”"
        ]
      }
    }
  },
